# Definition of Done — {{PROJECT_NAME}} (Go)

This is a Go project. The list below is the contract every change must meet before it can be called done. `/dod:checklist` reads this file and surfaces unmet items.

## Universal criteria

- [ ] All new exported functions, types, and packages have a godoc comment (`// FuncName does X.`) that explains behavior, parameters, and error semantics.
- [ ] No new `TODO` / `FIXME` / `XXX` / `HACK` markers in the diff.
- [ ] No function ships with `panic("not implemented")`, `panic("unimplemented")`, or an empty body.
- [ ] No `// nolint:` markers added in the diff (escape hatches). If a lint must be suppressed, link an issue in the comment.
- [ ] No constructor `NewX()` left returning `&X{}` / `X{}` with critical fields uninitialized.
- [ ] No `_ = err` or `_, _ = ...` that silently discards an error path.
- [ ] No `if err != nil { return err }` that forwards an error without wrapping (`fmt.Errorf("doing X: %w", err)`).

## Tests

- [ ] Tests added for every new code path (table-driven preferred where applicable).
- [ ] No `t.Skip(...)` added in this diff to bypass a failure.
- [ ] No `assert.True(t, true)` / `assert.Equal(t, x, x)` / `assert.NoError(t, nil)` tautologies.
- [ ] Every new `TestX` function makes at least one real assertion (`t.Errorf`, `t.Fatalf`, `assert.*`, `require.*`).
- [ ] No `t.Log("TODO: ...")` left in a passing test.
- [ ] `go test ./...` passes locally.
- [ ] `go test -race ./...` passes for code touching concurrency primitives.

## Build & vet

- [ ] `go build ./...` succeeds.
- [ ] `go vet ./...` is clean.
- [ ] `go mod tidy` produces no diff (no unused dependencies, no missing ones).
- [ ] If `golangci-lint` is configured for the repo, `golangci-lint run` is clean.

## End-to-end probe

- [ ] For every new HTTP handler / CLI command, paste the exact `curl` / CLI invocation that exercises it, with the observed response or stdout, into the PR description.
- [ ] For library functions, paste a `go run ./cmd/<example>/main.go` or `go test -run TestExample -v ./pkg/...` output.

